It was interesting to note that when the separated GQDs solution and RGO framework were remixed by adjusting the solution pH to 1.0, the recombination between GQDs and RGO was achieved, but a longer time was needed. As shown in Fig. 6
                        a, after 48 h, fluorescence intensity of the mixed solution was significantly weakened, and even negligible. As contrast, for a pure GQDs solution, no fluorescence attenuation occurred after acid treatment for dozens of hours (Fig. S8). Those results displayed that free GQDs were reloaded into RGO to form the cross-linking networks through the reconstruction of the hydrogen bonding interactions. It noted that the reversible process, referred to stripping and reloading of GQDs in the hydrogel at pH = 1.0 and pH = 13.0, respectively, could repeat several times and the fluorescence intensities of the solutions remained constant with the pH changed from 13.0 to 1.0 for 4 cycles (Fig. 6b). In brief, all above results demonstrated that GQDs-GSH exhibited the reversibility of engineering-separation-reengineering process under the pH stimulus (Fig. 7
                        ), owing to abundant pH-dependent hydrogen bonding between GQDs and RGO. In addition, the FT-IR and XPS spectra (Fig. S9) gave full proofs to point out that the type of functional group and hydrogen bonding mode have no difference between the reconstructed hydrogel (named as GQDs-GSH-R) and the original hydrogel, indicating that GQDs-GSH has a superior self-assembly repeatability.
